For a more concrete example, consider the free distributive lattice 2[x] generated by a single element. The space \operatorname {Spec} 2[x] \cong  2 is the Sierpinski space, with the stalks

\usepackage {tikz-cd}\usepackage {quiver}
  \begin {tikzcd}
    {2[x]} \ar [r, "x = 1"] & 2 \\
    \bullet  & \bullet 
    \arrow [dashed, no head, from=1-1, to=2-1]
    \arrow [dashed, no head, from=1-2, to=2-2]
    \arrow [from=2-1, to=2-2]
  \end {tikzcd}

fr:tree.fr:mainmatter:
Suppose X \cong  \operatorname {Spec} D and Y \cong  \operatorname {Spec} E with U = p and V = q for some p\in  D and q\in  E, with an isomorphism u : D/p \cong  E/q. This way, the global section A of X \cup  Y by the sheaf condition is given by the following pullback,

\usepackage {tikz-cd}\usepackage {quiver}
  \begin {tikzcd}
    A \ar [r, "f"] \ar [d, "g"'] \ar [dr, "\lrcorner "{anchor = center, pos = 0.125}, draw = none] & D \ar [d] \\ 
    E \ar [r] & E/q \cong  D/p
  \end {tikzcd}


We show that the map f : A \to  D is isomorphic to A \to  A/(q,1). First since by construction f(q,1) = 1, there is a factorisation

\usepackage {tikz-cd}\usepackage {quiver}
  \begin {tikzcd}
    A \ar [r, "f"] \ar [d, two heads] & D \\ 
    A/(q,1) \ar [ur, dashed, "f"']
  \end {tikzcd}


f : A/(q,1) \to  D must be surjective: For any d\in  D, along the isomorphism u D/p \cong  E/q we know that (u(d\wedge  p),d) \in  A, whose image under f is d. On the other hand, it must also be injective: For any (e,d),(e',d')\in  A/(q,1), suppose d = d'. By construction, we must then have ud = e and ud' = e', which implies e = e'. Hence, (e,d) = (e',d') in A/(q,1). Similarly, g : A \to  E will be isomorphic to A \to  A/(1,p).

This way, by Theorem  we get a canonical function
 X \cup  Y \to  \operatorname {Spec} A 
We show this is an isomorphism. It suffices to show it is a homeomorphism of topological spaces, because the sheaves are glued together. But this is the same as stating prime filters in A are either prime filters in D or E, modulo the identification. This follows from Proposition .

fr:mainmatter.html:p:

It is then easy to see \mathbb {N} is Noetherian. Hence, by Theorem  prime ideals in \mathbb {N} are exactly meet-irreducible elements. According to this we can compute the spectrum of \mathbb {N} as below

\usepackage {tikz-cd}\usepackage {quiver}
\begin {tikzpicture}
  \node  (2) at (0,0) {2};
  \node  (3) at (1,0) {3};
  \node  (5) at (2,0) {5};
  \node  (p) at (3,0) {$\cdots $};

  \node  (4) at (0,1) {4};
  \node  (9) at (1,1) {9};
  \node  (25) at (2,1) {25};
  \node  (p2) at (3,1) {$\cdots $};

  \node  (8) at (0,2) {$\vdots $};
  \node  (27) at (1,2) {$\vdots $};
  \node  (125) at (2,2) {$\vdots $};
  \node  (pn) at (3,2) {$\vdots $};

  \node  (0) at (1.5,3) {0};

  \path [->] (2) edge (4);
  \path [->] (4) edge (8);
  \path [->] (8) edge (0);

  \path [->] (3) edge (9);
  \path [->] (9) edge (27);
  \path [->] (27) edge (0);

  \path [->] (5) edge (25);
  \path [->] (25) edge (125);
  \path [->] (125) edge (0);

  \path [->] (p) edge (p2);
  \path [->] (p2) edge (pn);
  \path [->] (pn) edge (0);
\end {tikzpicture}


where each number p above corresponds to the prime filter of those elements not containing p has a factor. Notice for any n\in \mathbb {N},
 O_n = \{p^k\mid p^k\not {\mid } n\}. 
Since each natural number only contains finitely many prime factors, it is easier to describe the closed sets,
 C_n = \{p^k\mid p^k \mid  n\} = \downarrow  p_1^{k_1} \cup  \cdots  \cup  \downarrow  p_m^{k_m}, 
where n = p_1^{k_1} \cdots  p_m^{k_m} is the prime factorisation of n.
